  <h1 class="article__title reveal">The Block-Shaped Designer</h1>

  <p class="reveal">
    The design industry spent the last decade celebrating the T-shaped designer.
    Deep expertise in one area, just enough breadth to collaborate across disciplines.
    We built career ladders around it, hired for it, structured entire design orgs
    around the idea that depth beats breadth every single time.
  </p>

  <p class="reveal">
    That model made sense when teams were bigger and there were specialists in every
    seat. Your depth justified your presence. Your breadth made you collaborative.
    But the context that made the T-shape valuable has fundamentally changed.
  </p>

  <h2 class="reveal">Why the T-shape is cracking</h2>

  <p class="reveal">
    Three things are happening simultaneously.
  </p>

  <p class="reveal">
    <strong>Teams are flatter and leaner.</strong> The era of the big design org with a
    research team, a systems team, and a UX team is fading. You're more likely to be
    a team of two covering what used to be a team of eight. The researcher moved on
    and wasn't backfilled. The PM is stretched across multiple products. Engineering
    is heads down and doesn't have time to be your thought partner.
  </p>

  <p class="reveal">
    <strong>The pace of expectations has accelerated.</strong> Stakeholders don't want to
    wait three weeks for a prototype. They want something real, fast, so they can react
    and make decisions. The designer who can move from idea to testable artifact in hours,
    not days, is the one who shapes the conversation. If you're slow, someone else fills
    the vacuum.
  </p>

  <p class="reveal">
    <strong>AI is collapsing the distance between disciplines.</strong> The gap between
    design and code used to be wide enough that specialization made sense. But now a
    designer with the right tools can generate working UI, validate flows with real
    interactions, and hand off something genuinely close to production ready. The walls
    between roles are getting thinner. The T-shaped model assumed those walls were
    load-bearing. They're not anymore.
  </p>

  <h2 class="reveal">Enter the block-shaped designer</h2>

  <p class="reveal">
    Picture a block instead of a T. It's not a mile deep and an inch wide. It's not an
    inch deep and a mile wide. It's genuinely solid across several different dimensions.
    Multiple areas of real capability, not just surface familiarity.
  </p>

  <p class="reveal">
    The block-shaped designer isn't a jack of all trades who's mediocre at everything.
    That's the fear, and it's worth calling out directly. This isn't about spreading
    yourself so thin that you stop being useful. It's about being dangerous in multiple
    different directions.
  </p>

  <blockquote class="reveal">
    The value isn't that a block-shaped designer can do all of these things all the time.
    The value is that when the team needs someone to flex, you're the one flexing.
  </blockquote>

  <p class="reveal">
    A block-shaped designer can sit in a product strategy conversation and actually
    contribute something meaningful. Not because they're pretending to be a PM, but
    because they understand user problems, business constraints, and what's actually
    buildable. They can jump into a dev handoff and speak the language of components,
    tokens, and edge cases. They can run quick research sprints when there's no
    researcher. They can write UX copy when there's no content strategist.
  </p>

  <h2 class="reveal">The four pillars</h2>

  <p class="reveal">
    From what I've seen and lived, the block-shaped designer operates across four areas:
  </p>

  <p class="reveal">
    <strong>1. Speed as leverage.</strong> The block-shaped designer is genuinely fast in
    their tools. Not just competent — fast. They use auto layout fluently, build with
    components, and have set up their workspace so the tool is almost invisible. It's
    just thinking made visual. The faster you can externalize an idea, the more ideas
    you can explore, and the more options you bring to the conversation.
  </p>

  <p class="reveal">
    <strong>2. AI-powered prototyping and validation.</strong> They're not waiting for a
    developer to make something feel real. They're using tools like Figma Make, Claude
    Code, or Replit to generate working UI from design intent. They spin up quick
    functional prototypes to pressure test their thinking, generate copy variations,
    and reason through edge cases. The goal is learning, not production code. They
    compress the validation loop — putting something in front of a real user that
    behaves like software, not just looks like it.
  </p>

  <p class="reveal">
    <strong>3. Systems thinking that actually ships.</strong> It's not enough to build the
    system and hand it off. The expectation now is that you understand how your design
    system maps to your component library, how tokens flow to code, how you use that
    structure to make the last mile of the handoff almost automatic. Systems thinking
    isn't just a design skill anymore. It's a translation skill.
  </p>

  <p class="reveal">
    <strong>4. Owning the design-to-development handoff.</strong> Most designers treat the
    handoff as the end of their job. But this is where design decisions either survive or
    get quietly undone. Details get approximated, decisions get made without you. The
    block-shaped designer stays close. They annotate with intent, not just measurements.
    They document the why behind decisions, not just the what. They show up at the
    engineering conversation before implementation starts, not after.
  </p>

  <h2 class="reveal">What this looks like in my work</h2>

  <p class="reveal">
    I didn't set out to become a block-shaped designer. I just kept saying yes to the
    things that needed doing.
  </p>

  <p class="reveal">
    At <strong>KBC</strong>, I designed 186 conversations for Kate, their digital assistant,
    and was the first designer to integrate LLMs into what had been a fully rule-based
    chatbot. That wasn't a separate AI team's job — it was me sitting at the intersection
    of conversation design, UX, and machine learning, figuring out how to make a banking
    chatbot actually helpful.
  </p>

  <p class="reveal">
    At <strong>Nitra Academy</strong>, there was no dev team. An exam center running on
    spreadsheets needed a real system. So I designed it, built the MVP in Zoho Creator,
    and shipped it. It's been in daily use since. That's not a designer handing off a
    Figma file — that's a designer shipping a product.
  </p>

  <p class="reveal">
    At <strong>VRT MAX</strong>, I design the streaming experience for Belgium's
    most-watched platform. But I also think about design systems, component architecture,
    and how design decisions translate into code that developers can actually build.
  </p>

  <p class="reveal">
    And this portfolio? I built it with <strong>Claude Code</strong>. Every page, every
    animation, every interaction. Not because I had to — because I believe designers
    who can ship their own work have an unfair advantage. The validation loop between
    "what if" and "here it is" gets infinitely shorter.
  </p>

  <h2 class="reveal">The behavioral side</h2>

  <p class="reveal">
    Beyond skills, the block-shaped designer has a few behavioral traits that show up
    consistently:
  </p>

  <ul class="reveal">
    <li>
      <strong>Context switching without losing the thread.</strong> Modern product work
      is noisy — meetings, async channels, shifting priorities. But the block-shaped
      designer can move between a strategy conversation and a pixel-level decision
      without losing altitude in either one.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Influence without authority.</strong> They're not waiting to be asked. They
      bring a point of view to product conversations. They have opinions about what
      should be built, not just how it should look.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Learning as a constant practice.</strong> The tools are changing fast —
      every single day. The block-shaped designer treats keeping up as part of the job,
      not a burden on top of it. They're experimenting with new tools before they're
      obvious, and sharing what they learn with their team.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Comfortable being imperfect in public.</strong> Fast teams need
      work-in-progress thinking, not polished presentations. The block-shaped designer
      can share a half-baked prototype and frame it correctly: "I want to learn from
      this, not show it off." That vulnerability is a superpower in teams that move
      quickly.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="reveal">How to start building towards it</h2>

  <p class="reveal">
    If this resonates, here's where to begin:
  </p>

  <p class="reveal">
    <strong>Start with your secondary skill, not your primary one.</strong> You probably
    already have your depth. The move now is figuring out which adjacent area would make
    you most useful to your team right now, and genuinely getting good at it. Not
    YouTube-video good — actually using it in real projects.
  </p>

  <p class="reveal">
    <strong>Pick an AI tool and use it for real work.</strong> Don't experiment on side
    projects at home in secret. Use it on something that matters in your day-to-day. Use
    Figma Make on a real prototype. Use Claude Code to build out a flow you're designing.
    You'll find what's real and what's hype much faster when the stakes are real.
  </p>

  <p class="reveal">
    <strong>Stop waiting for permission to expand your scope.</strong> A lot of designers
    sit on the edge of their defined role, waiting for an invitation. Nobody's going to
    officially expand your role for you. Just start contributing to the conversation you
    want to be part of. Bring a point of view to the roadmap. Write up a research
    synthesis even if you're not a researcher. Sit in on engineering planning. Do it
    consistently enough and your scope expands on its own.
  </p>

  <p class="reveal">
    <strong>Invest in your handoff process.</strong> If there's one thing that will
    immediately change how engineering perceives your work, it's tightening up your
    handoff. Pick a project and document it like it actually matters. Write the
    annotations. Link to the specs. Show up to the kickoff. Build a prototype. See
    what changes in your role.
  </p>

  <h2 class="reveal">The reframe</h2>

  <p class="reveal">
    The block-shaped designer isn't trying to be everything to everyone. They're not
    trying to replace the engineer or the PM or the researcher. What they're doing is
    building enough capability across enough dimensions that they can contribute
    meaningfully when those roles aren't covered. When the team needs someone to flex,
    when the moment calls for more than one thing — you're there.
  </p>

  <p class="reveal">
    This isn't about being average at everything. It's about being competent enough in
    multiple areas that your creative leverage is significantly higher than someone
    who's only operating in one lane.
  </p>

  <p class="reveal">
    The teams that move fastest aren't built from specialists siloed in their lanes.
    They're built from people who can reach across, who can flex, who can make an
    impact in more than one direction. That's the block. That's what this moment is
    asking for.
  </p>
